message.content: One of the most significant events that happened in South Africa in the past 100 years is the end of apartheid and the subsequent election of Nelson Mandela as the country's first black president. Apartheid was a system of racial segregation and discrimination enforced by the white minority government, which lasted from 1948 to 1994. The dismantling of apartheid and the peaceful transition to a democratic government marked a major turning point in South African history and symbolized the triumph of equality and justice. Mandela's presidency and his efforts towards reconciliation and nation-building have had a lasting impact on South Africa and the world.
